f. Main/core directives of Docker
University of Information Technology and
Communications1.FROM  directive :
▪Used  to specify  the base  image  that  the container  will inherit . ▪Each  Dockerfile  must  start  with  at least  one  FROM . ▪Example : FROM  openjdk :11 => Use  the openjdk :11 image  as a base  to build  a
container  to run the Java  application . 2.COPY  directive :
▪Used  to copy  files/folders  from  the host  machine  (where  you  write  the Dockerfile)
into  the container . ▪Example : COPY  target/myapp .war  /usr/local/tomcat/webapps/  => Copy  the
myapp .war  file from  the target  folder  on the host  machine  to the webapps  folder  in
the Tomcat  container . f. Main/core directives of Docker
University of Information Technology and
Communications3. ADD  directive :
▪Similar  to COPY  but more  powerful  (Can  automatically  extract  .tar files,  Supports  URLs  to
download  files from  the Internet)
▪Example : ADD  https ://example .com/app .tar.gz /app/  => Download  the app .tar.gz file
from  the Internet,  copy  it to /app/  in the container  and  automatically  extract  it. 4. RUN  directive :
▪Used  to run commands  during  the image  build  process,  usually  to install  packages,  set up
the environment . ▪Example : RUN  apt-get update  && apt-get install  -y curl  => Update  the package  list
and  install  the curl  tool  into  the image . f. Main/core directives of Docker
University of Information Technology and
Communications5. ENV  directive :
▪Used  to declare  environment  variables  in the container . ▪Example : ENV  APP_HOME=/usr/local/myapp  => Create  the APP_HOME  environment
variable . Then  it can  be used  in the Dockerfile  or when  the container  is running
6. WORKDIR  directive :
▪Sets the default  working  directory  in the container . Subsequent  commands  (RUN,  CMD,
COPY ,  …) will be executed  in this directory . ▪Example : dockerfile :
WORKDIR  /app
COPY  . . RUN  javac  Main .java
CMD  ["java" ,  "Main"]Meaning:
▪Set the default working directory to /app. ▪Copy all source code to /app. ▪Compile the Main.java file.

